metadata.recording_metadata_summary: This recording is from a middle-school participating in the PLUS tutoring program. This school is called Urban Pathways. Students in this school use Chromebooks to access Zoom and generally use the math software Khan. The teacher in the classroom is named Antolik-Allen-Bennick, although other teachers may be present. The tutor assigned to this classroom is named Victor Miene, although other tutors may be present.

events.description: Zoom interface shows black screens with names 'asayvio' and 'Victor Miene'. Victor is visible on camera adjusting his hat.

events.text: Hello?
Can... Can you hear me? Are you there?
Hello? Um, are you there? Can you hear me?
Hello?
Um, hi.
Hello, hello.
So, my name is Victor and I'm your tutor for today.
I wasn't doing nothing...
Just tell me to stop talking... Worry about yourself.
Hello?
Where's my pencil?
Hello? Yeah, I hear you. Um, how... how do you pronounce your name?

events.to_window: Khan Academy - Negative fractions on the number line
events.details: Student starts screen sharing Khan Academy.
Student switches back to the Zoom application window. Camera turns on briefly showing the student adjusting headset.
Clicks the Annotation pencil icon in Zoom.

events.description: Screen share content goes black or is paused.

events.text: Diontai.
Oh, Diontai. Um, my name is Victor.

events.text: And I'm your tutor for today.
Okay.

events.text: Okay. Yeah.

events.text: A B C D...
Um... Are you... are you guys working on Khan today too? Oh yeah, I see.

Day, how is your day going?
Mm, fine. Um, I had a class some moments ago and... right now I'm working. I'd say pretty good.
Yeah. So, we're supposed to be working on number lines today.

events.details: Student types '14' into the answer box.

events.text: You said 14... 10 plus 14.

events.details: Student deletes '14'.
Student types '-1/1'.
Clicks Check. Result: 'Not quite!'.

events.text: Uh, that is not a fraction.
No.
Who loves to cuss?
Nobody.
I know you were cussing.

events.details: Student switches to the Zoom window.

events.description: Camera view of student appears. He gestures 'shhh' or adjusts his audio.

events.text: Um, Diontai, if you can hear me I'll be back... let me say hi to the... the other student. I'll be with you in a sec.

events.description: Student sits quietly, looking around, waiting.

events.text: What? I missed that again?
Um, if you can... if you can hear me I'll be back in a sec. Do you know how to do the question?
Yeah I know how to do it.
Uh let me... let me see. Cause...
Let me see what your answer is.

events.details: Switch back to Khan Academy.
Student highlights the text 'Look at the number line below. What point is marked on the number line?'
Opens a new tab (Ctrl+T).
Clicks back to the Khan Academy tab.

events.text: So if that is zero... then negative...

events.details: Moves cursor over the tick marks on the number line between -1 and 0.
Types '-1/1' again.
Clicks Check. Result: 'Not quite yet...'.

events.text: Um, so... um it's okay if you... you're not getting it right at first.
What you need to know, you can check from zero. From zero to one, they are like... you can count the number of... vertical lines there are.
One, two, three, four, five, six.

events.details: Moves cursor along the tick marks from 0 to 1, counting them.

events.text: Yeah, so you see that there are six.
And the width of... the... the line from zero to one is like... one.
Um, so you have to divide one by six places.
Five?
If you divide one by six... no it's six, not five. I thought it was five too but when I counted it, it was six.
So... when you divide one by six places you get... 0.16666... that's like 0.167.
So for every time you move... to the left or to the right, you are going to be adding either positive 0.16 or negative 0.16.
In this case you are moving to the left... from negative one. So you're supposed to have negative one...

events.details: Student types '-0/16'.

events.text: And they said your answer should be a fraction. So that's something else.
Your answer should be a fraction, so anytime you move to the left you're supposed to have one over six... minus one over six instead of 0.16.
So for this one, you have negative one... since you were on negative one.

events.details: Student clears field and types '-0/1'.

events.text: Instead of zero, you can remove the zero.
Can you hear me Diontai?
Yeah I can hear you.

Uh, okay. So, what I'm saying is that you were at negative one and you're moving to the left. So you're supposed to add... for every time you go to the left you're supposed to add like a negative one over six.

events.details: Student types '0/1'.

events.text: Oh, no no no no. That's still not it.
Let me... let me see if I can pull up my whiteboard.

events.description: Screen share changes. Tutor shares a white screen (whiteboard).

events.text: Can you see my whiteboard?
Yes.

events.details: Tutor draws a horizontal line segment, adds marks for '-1' and writes '-1/6' (or similar math notation).

events.text: It's going to give you negative one... then one by six.

events.details: Tutor writes '-1 1/6'.

events.text: Yeah. So this is how it works.
Each movement is worth one over six... in this case.
Do you want to... try that out?

Do you guys have to leave?
A B C D E F G...
